</disciplines><abstract>&lt;p&gt;This paper explores the workings of white supremacy within a rural Brazilian context. France Winddance Twine’s &lt;em&gt;Racism in a Racial Democracy&lt;/em&gt; serves as an ideological basis for this analysis of Carolina Maria de Jesus’s &lt;em&gt;Bitita’s Diary, &lt;/em&gt;and shows how systemic and rampant white supremacy has weighed on the psyche of Afro-Brazilians and how it persists to the present day.&lt;/p&gt;</abstract>
